### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It will use a web framework (e.g., Flask) to handle routing, serve pages, process user inputs (like placing bids), read/write data from/to the local text files in the `data/` directory, and implement all business logic for the nine pages. Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into this single file is efficient and maintainable.

- **templates/**  
  This directory contains all HTML template files for the web application pages, each corresponding to one of the nine pages specified in the requirements. Templates will include the specified elements with their IDs for frontend rendering and interaction.

  - `dashboard.html` — Auction Dashboard page  
  - `auction_catalog.html` — Auction Catalog page  
  - `auction_details.html` — Auction Details page  
  - `place_bid.html` — Place Bid page  
  - `bid_history.html` — Bid History page  
  - `auction_categories.html` — Auction Categories page  
  - `winners.html` — Winners page  
  - `trending_auctions.html` — Trending Auctions page  
  - `auction_status.html` — Auction Status page  

- **static/**  
  Contains static assets used by the web pages.

  - `css/styles.css` — Stylesheet for consistent styling of the web application.  
  - `js/scripts.js` — JavaScript for client-side interactivity, such as filtering, sorting, and navigation button actions.  
  - `images/` — Folder for auction item images referenced in `auctions.txt` (e.g., watch.jpg, iphone.jpg).

- **data/**  
  Contains all the local text files used for data storage and retrieval as per the defined formats:

  - `auctions.txt` — Auction items data  
  - `categories.txt` — Auction categories data  
  - `bids.txt` — Bids data  
  - `winners.txt` — Winners data  
  - `bid_history.txt` — Bid history data  
  - `items.txt` — Items data  
  - `trending.txt` — Trending auctions data  

This file structure and naming convention align with the project requirements, support maintainability, and facilitate clear separation of concerns between backend logic, frontend presentation, static assets, and data storage."

